## The Cattle Superstitions (136-144)

This is where the surah gets its name.

The pre-Islamic Arabs had invented elaborate rules around their livestock. They dedicated certain cattle to idols, declared some animals off-limits for women, and prohibited riding or eating certain types. They believed these were divine rules handed down through tradition.

The Quran challenges them directly:

> *"Say: Do you see what God has sent down to you for provision, and you have made some of it unlawful and some lawful? Say: Has God permitted you, or do you invent lies against God?"* (59)

**Who told you this?** Where is the revelation that says women can't eat from this animal, or that this cow belongs to an idol? There is none. You made it up and then claimed God said so.

The surah then goes through specific examples:

> *"Eight pairs: of sheep two, and of goats two. Say: Is it the two males He has forbidden, or the two females, or what the wombs of the two females contain? Inform me with knowledge, if you are truthful."* (143)

The argument: if you claim God prohibited certain animals, then *which ones exactly?* The males? The females? The offspring? You can't answer because there is no divine basis for it. You inherited these superstitions from your ancestors and never questioned them.

