## Don't Invent Religion (148-150)

The broader point extends beyond cattle. The Meccans had built an entire system of religious customs with no basis in revelation. They just assumed their ancestors were right.

> *"Those who associated others with God will say: 'If God had willed, we would not have associated anything, nor would our fathers, nor would we have prohibited anything.' Likewise did those before them deny until they tasted Our punishment."* (148)

They use God's will as an excuse: *"If God didn't want us doing this, He would have stopped us."* The Quran rejects this logic. God giving you free will doesn't mean He approves of your choices.

> *"Say: Do you have any knowledge you can produce for us? You follow nothing but assumption, and you are only guessing."* (148)

Bring evidence. Not tradition, not "our fathers did it," not assumptions. Actual evidence. If you can't produce it, you're guessing and calling it religion.

