## The Commandments (151-153)

The surah closes with a powerful list of moral commands. Scholars sometimes call this the **Islamic equivalent of the Ten Commandments**:

> *"Say: Come, I will recite to you what your Lord has actually prohibited:"* (151)

Note the framing. After an entire section about *invented* prohibitions, the Quran says: *here's what God actually forbade*:

1. **Don't associate anything with God**
2. **Be good to your parents**
3. **Don't kill your children out of fear of poverty**. God provides for you and them.
4. **Don't approach immoralities**, whether open or secret
5. **Don't kill a soul that God has made sacred**, except by right of justice
6. **Don't touch an orphan's wealth** except to improve it, until they reach maturity
7. **Give full measure and weight** with fairness
8. **When you speak, be just**, even if it concerns a relative
9. **Fulfill the covenant of God**

> *"This is what He has commanded you, so that you may use reason."* (151)

No superstition. No invented taboos. No cattle rituals. Just these: worship God alone, respect life, protect the vulnerable, be honest, and keep your word.

---

## The Straight Path (153-165)

The surah ends by returning to its core message:

> *"Indeed, this is My path, straight. So follow it, and do not follow other ways, for they will separate you from His way."* (153)

One path, clearly laid out. The "other ways" are the invented traditions, the idol worship, the superstitions, the guesswork that people dress up as religion.

The final verse ties everything together:

> *"Say: Indeed, my prayer, my sacrifice, my living, and my dying are for God, Lord of the worlds. He has no partner. And this I have been commanded, and I am the first of those who submit."* (162-163)

Everything, from prayer to death, belongs to God. No partners, no intermediaries. This is what Abraham concluded when the stars set, what every prophet after him taught, and what Muhammad is now repeating to the people of Mecca.
